@node Introduction "Introduction"


                               @{b}Introduction@{ub}


International language support has never been a major force of the Amiga to
say the least. Of course we've been blessed with the locale.library which
is just great and still tops other OS, but apart from that, dealing with
languages that use another encoding system than the ISO-Latin1 (ASCII
extension that contains special characters of most Western European
languages) is not very handy. AmigaOS has no clue of what Unicode is and
can't manually switch from one encoding system to another. That means you
can't use both (for example) French and Czech at the same time, same with
every other Eastern European languages. Things are even worse with languages
that use different alphabets like Russian or Greek: in this case you
wouldn't even have regular latin characters right since you'd be using a
totally different font.

But the challenge I wanted to face was a tad tougher. After beeing
introduced to Chinese characters by a Chinese friend, I got interested in
the different aspects of this exotic writing. I had always been intrigued
by how Eastern Asian people could type in their own language - implying
using thousands of different characters - using a keyboard of about a hundred
keys. She showed me the method commonly used in PRC (People's Republic of
China) that allows people to write about as fast as we can type English
texts. This method works quite well, at least on Windows 2000. More and
more interested in Chinese characters, I decided to have a look of what's
be done on Amiga. A quick look on Aminet proved what I was expecting: very
little indeed. A patch to display Chinese characters (text/misc/Chinese.lha),
a MUI Chinese text viewer (text/show/hzv2_0b.lha) and a few rather useless
UNIX ports.

The patch is a good idea, but the implementation has two flaws that makes it,
in my opinion, unusable. First it patches all texts, including small ones
that will be patched with a Chinese font so small the display will be
rubbished. More important, it patches all non ASCII characters, meaning you
can kiss goodbye to all accents in French, umlauts in German and other
particularities of European languages.

The MUI Chinese text viewer is slow, has bad design for scrolling and is
crippled for a shareware fee way too expensive.

The UNIX ports, although interesting, don't bring any Chinese capabilities
to the AmigaOS. They mostly consist of very simple format converters.

So I decided to make a Chinese text viewer myself that would not be a patch
to avoid the problems mentioned above. I started to look for docs on the
web and did the coding. I came up with a text viewer that could read @{"GB2312" LINK GB2312}
encoded texts. That became, as far as I know, the first really usable Chinese
text viewer on AmigaOS. But during my Chinese search on the web and Aminet,
I came across a file that made me think I could do much, much better!

I realized I could do a so-called Chinese IME system, like the one my
Chinese friend showed me a couple of months before on Windows 2000.
First off it was clear: I had no intention to program a text editor so I
had to communicate with an external text editor, like a MUI editor class or a
program like CygnusED via Arexx. I tried both methods and decided to only
keep the Arexx option. But that meant I had to go back to this patch idea
since the external editor has no idea of what a Chinese character is. Still
convinced that the already existing patch was too flawed to be usable, I
made my own patch that will only patch under certain circumstances and will
not trash special European characters.

And there you go! Here's the first Chinese IME solution for the Amiga!

@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements"


                               @{b}Requirements@{ub}


 - Workbench 2.0+
 - @{"MUI" LINK MUI}
 - MUI Image Button custom class
 - RexxMast running
