@node Installation "Installation"


                               @{b}Installation@{ub}


Straightforward enough, so I don't bother to provide an installation
script.

 - Copy the content of the fonts directory in FONTS:

That will copy the Chinese font (actually not a font but a raw bitmap file)
and a 16pt font called @{b}wlook@{ub} that is appropriate for text patching.


 - Copy the file ChineseTextPatch wherever you want.

C: sounds like a nice place. You may leave it in the program directory.


That's it.

@endnode

@node Tutorial "Short tutorial"


                              @{b}Short tutorial@{ub}


Instead of giving a boring reference, here's a quick tutorial to get your
hands quickly on this program.


@{fg shine}Preparation@{fg text}

Make sure RexxMast is running. Also, have an instance of Cygnus Ed running.
Run the patch ChineseTextPatch which will allow CED to display Chinese texts.
Launch the program. Have CED and the program run on the same public screen,
the Workbench for instance. You're ready to go...


@{fg shine}First sentence@{fg text}

First, you need to have CED use a font that will be patched by
ChineseTextPatch. @{i}wlook@{ui} is such a font. You can select it quickly
in the menu Project/Select Chinese Font.

Now, say we want to type "I love you" in Chinese. In Chinese, "I love you"
is "wo3 ai4 ni3". The numbers denote the @{"tones" LINK ChineseNotes}.

So, type "wo" in the program string gadget. You see on the right all the
Chinese characters that are pronounced "wo". There are 19 of them. You can
reduce the number of characters by precising the tone you're looking for.
So append "3" to the gadget to get "wo3". You see that only one character
corresponds to "wo" in the third tone. Click on the character. It is added
to the CED buffer, at the cursor position. Normally you should see a Chinese
character. If instead you see two strange characters, that means the patch
is not active. You either didn't run it or you didn't select a correct
font.

So, we have our first character, "wo" which means "I". Let's get our second
character, "ai", which means "to love". There again you can enter "ai" or
"ai4". The first choice will display 23 characters, the second one 12.
Either way, the character we're interested in is the first one. To select
it quickly you can press space in the string gadget. Pressing space in the
string gadget will always select the first Chinese character.

Let's get the last character, "ni" which means "you". Okay, you know enough
to select it quickly: again, it's the first one of the list.

Finally, let's add a stop at the end of the phrase. Of course you can
directly go to CED and add a stop yourself, but since we're typing in
Chinese, let's get a Chinese stop. Chinese stops are not a simple dot but a
circle. To get it, simply enter "." in the string gadget.

That's it! You've got your first sentence in Chinese!


@{fg shine}Another one!@{fg text}

Let's write another sentence: "This book is new". In Chinese it's said
"zhe4 ben3 shu1 shi4 xin1 de".

I let you write the first four characters: they are the first ones when you
enter the transcription with the tone.
"zhe4" means "this" and "ben3" is a word without real meaning used for
gramatical reasons.
"shu1" means book.
"shi4" means "to be"

Now, for "xin1". This character will not come first, even if you precise
the tone. It's in fact the second character in the list. To select it,
press the tab key until the second character is highlighted, then press
return. So, when the character you want is not the first in the list, the
fastest way to access it is to use the tab key.

The last one, "de": straightforward, it's the first one on the list.

Again, finish up the sentence with a lovely Chinese stop.

@{b}Note@{ub}: "de" has no tone. It has a neutral tone. To select the neutral tone,
you can always consider it's a fifth tone. So, you'll type "de5".

@endnode

@node SpecialChars "Special characters"


                            @{b}Special characters@{ub}


Besides Chinese characters, @{"GB2312" LINK GB2312} encoding offers several special
character sets, like specific Japanese characters and different European
alphabets.

@{fg shine}Cyrillic alphabet@{fg text}
You can type in cyrillic. To type in uppercase, type in @{i}CYRIL@{ui} in the pinyin
string gadget and choose the wanted character. To type in lowercase, type
in @{i}cyril@{ui}.

@{fg shine}Greek alphabet@{fg text}
You can type in greek. To type in uppercase, type in @{i}GREEK@{ui} in the pinyin
string gadget and choose the wanted character. To type in lowercase, type
in @{i}greek@{ui}.

@{fg shine}Hiragana@{fg text}
To enter an @{"hiragana" LINK Glossary}, type in @{i}hira@{ui} and select the wanted character.

@{fg shine}Katakana@{fg text}
To enter a @{"katakana" LINK Glossary}, type in @{i}kata@{ui} and select the wanted character.


@{b}Note:@{ub} The Japanese facility is here for the sake of completeness.
It's certainly not a fast way to enter a Japanese character, but anyway,
this is a Chinese IME, not a Japanese one. It would be silly to write in
Japanese since that would mean using Chinese pronounciation for writing
@{"kanji" LINK Glossary}, and would imply the use of @{"simplified" LINK TraditionalVsSimplified} characters whereas Japan uses
different simplified characters.
There's been two Japanese endeavours that are available on Aminet if
you're interested. Namely, @{i}Kezako@{ui} and @{i}Jiwa@{ui}.

@endnode

@node CharOrder "Character order"


                              @{b}Character order@{ub}


To improve typing efficiency, when you are prompted to select a Chinese
character, the characters come sorted by frequency. So likely characters
come first and at the end of the list you'll find rarely used characters.

The character frequencies are stored in the file @{i}hanzi-freq.data@{ui} and the
frequencies are dynamically modified as you type. So that means the
frequencies will always be more accurate, provided you don't write rubbish
that is.

The provided hanzi-freq.data file has been generated by analysing two
different Chinese novels. That should give very satisfying results
eventhough about half of the 6763 characters are still without any
occurrence. It's not much of a problem since that means they REALLY are
rarely used. It is often said that when you know 2000 characters, you will
know 95% of all the characters you'll come across in your life, and when
you know 3000, you'll know 99% of the characters you'll see in your
lifetime. About 3500 are still without any occurrence, which means about
3200 have an occurrence: that's fair enough!

The program can run without the hanzi-freq.data file. In this case, all
frequencies will be considered as equals and when you leave, a new
hanzi-freq.data file will be creating, using the frequencies you will have
generated yourself.

@endnode

@node ChineseTextPatch "ChineseTextPatch"


                             @{b}ChineseTextPatch@{ub}


This program patches the @{i}Text()@{ui} function of the graphics.library to display
Chinese characters when detected. The patch recognizes @{"GB2312" LINK GB2312} encoding.
This program tries to detect special European characters such as @{i}é@{ui} and will
not translate them. However, when there are two such characters back to
back, there's no way to distinguish them from a Chinese character so
they'll be translated. But at least most problems will be fixed. The
characters are also only translated when the font size is exactely 16pt
high and 8pt wide, and is a non-proportinal font. That means the patch will
only print Chinese characters when you specifically ask a program to do so
(by selecting the right font).

Note: the current version is beta. Although the patch itself should be
completely stable, leaving the commodity can cause some problems. It has
nothing to do with the patch routine itself so as long as you don't leave
the patch, your system shouldn't suffer any instability.

@endnode

@node ChineseNotes "Notes on Chinese language"


                         @{b}Notes on Chinese language@{ub}


There is not one Chinese language but many different Chinese dialects.
Among the important dialects are Mandarin, Cantonese and the Shanghai
dialect. Mandarin is the official language of PRC. A person speaking a
dialect can't understand a person speaking another dialect, but can
communicate with this person using Chinese characters.
Basically, Chinese writing is the key of the unity of China.

Chinese is a monosyllabic language. That means that every word, every
particle is exactely one syllable long and will be represented by one
character. That is not exactely true since many words have two syllables or
more, but in this case they can be considered as compound words and will
take as many characters as their number of syllables. This characteristic
of Chinese language implies that Chinese language is very rich in term of
sounds.

@{fg shine}Tones@{fg text}
In Mandarin, there are four tones. A tone is a way of pronouncing a vowel.
These tones are numbered from 1 to 4.
@{b}Tone 1@{ub}: this tone is flat. The pitch of the sound is constant.
@{b}Tone 2@{ub}: this tone is ascending. The pitch of the sound increases while you
pronounce the vowel.
@{b}Tone 3@{ub}: this tone is descending-ascending. The pitch of the sound decreases
and then increases.
@{b}Tone 4@{ub}: this tone is descending. The pitch of the sound decreases.

There's also a fifth tone said to be neutral.

In @{"Pinyin transcription" LINK Pinyin}, the tone is represented with a accent on top of
the vowel. For computers that can't display these accents, the tone is
represented with a number at the end of the syllable. For instance, @{i}ming2@{ui}
means ming at the second tone.

@endnode

@node TraditionalVsSimplified "Traditional vs Simplified"


                         @{b}Traditional vs Simplified@{ub}


To say there are two different families of Chinese characters would be
quite exagerated but one must be aware that a character can be a bit
different depending where it is used.

Basically, in 1956, the Chinese government decided to simplify some
characters in order to fight illiteracy, thereby creating a new character
set that is called @{i}simplified@{ui} characters. The old character set is now
refered as @{i}traditional@{ui} characters.

The simplified characters are used in PRC, while Hong Kong, Taiwan and
Singapore still use traditional characters.
Japan also uses a simplified systems, but is different to the one adopted
in PRC.

Since this program uses @{"GB2312" LINK GB2312} encoding, simplified characters are used.

@endnode

@node GB2312 "GB2312"


                              @{b}GB2312 encoding@{ub}


GB2312 is the standard text encoding system in PRC. It's a kind of Chinese
ASCII. The size of a character depends on whether it's a Chinese character
or not. A Chinese character takes two bytes and a latin character takes one
byte. Without being too technical, let's say a GB2312 specific character is
coded in the range $A1A1-$FFFF. If a byte is not in this range, it's
considered as being an regular ASCII coding. In total, 6,763 Chinese
characters are available.

@endnode

@node Pinyin "Pinyin transcription"


                           @{b}Pinyin transcription@{ub}


Chinese language using ideograms, it makes it impossible to pronounce a
character you don't know. Thus, different transcription systems have been
created, so that people can have a phonetic representation of a character.
More than 35 transcription systems have been registered, which lead to some
confusion. Two transcription systems seem to stand out: @{i}Wade-Giles@{ui} and
@{i}Yale@{ui}.

To standardize the transcription systems, and also to standardize Chinese
pronounciation, back in the 1950's the Chinese government created a new
transcription system that virtually every Chinese knows, the @{i}Pinyin@{ui}.

@endnode

@node Glossary "Glossary"

 
                                @{b}Glossary@{ub}


@{fg shine}Hanzi@{fg text}
Literally, "Han's characters", in reference to the Han Dynasty. This term
denotes the Chinese characters that are in use in China, Taiwan, Japan...
A hanzi is therefore a Chinese character and is pronounced with exactely
one syllable. Non-Chinese languages that have imported Chinese characters
may use more than one syllable to pronounce a Chinese character.


@{fg shine}Kanji@{fg text}
Japanese pronounciation of Hanzi. Denotes the Chinese characters used in
Japan. These characters are the same as those used in China, except for
characters that have been @{"simplified" LINK TraditionalVsSimplified}.


@{fg shine}Hiragana@{fg text}
Alphabet used in Japan. Contrary to Western alphabet, a character denotes
a vowel and not a basic sound. Hiragana is used when a kanji is found to
be too uncommon.


@{fg shine}Katakana@{fg text}
Another alphabet used in Japan. Similar to hiragana. Katakana is used to
transcript foreign names into Japanese.


@{fg shine}Pinyin@{fg text}
Official transcription system used in PRC. Used to write Mandarin Chinese
with latin characters.


@{fg shine}Wade-Giles@{fg text}
Another transcription system. Initiated by Sir Thomas Wade in 1859 and
formulated later on by Herbet Giles. Still in use in Taiwan.


@{fg shine}Yale@{fg text}
Yet another transcription system. This one was developped in Yale
University. It's supposed to be very close to English pronounciation.


@{fg shine}PRC@{fg text}
Short for People's Republic of China. The official name of China since
1949.


@{fg shine}Mandarin@{fg text}
Official Chinese dialect in PRC. Spoken by about 70% of Chinese people,
including people from Beijing.

@endnode

@node Future "Future"


                                  @{b}Future@{ub}


 - Improve the speed of typing by allowing the user to quickly have access
   to the character he wants to enter.

 - Recognize multicharacter words to improve speed efficiency. That's a
   pretty tall order though, as it implies to have access to a Chinese
   dictionary.

 - Use of other text editor than Cygnus Ed. I'm open to all suggestions.
   The editor must have an Arexx port, have an Arexx command to enter an
   ASCII number and allow the user to select the font he wants to use.
   Not all editors react as well as CED for this. It depends on their
   internal refresh routines. CED is just ideal.

 - Find out what causes problems when quitting ChineseTextPatch. It's to do
   with the way I free the commodity resources and reply to the last
   messages received.

 - And finally, I'm open to any suggestion you can make.

@endnode

